6 a.m. The alarm clock ticks. He wakes up surrounded by lousy things on his bed.
He checks his phone and he realizes that he has to submit his story in a few hours. around, there's no Wi-Fi. He's staggering. He looks at a medical report next to him.

He sees his name under the tag Psychological evaluation. He reads: Chronic nicotine addiction, schizophrenia, PTSD.

He takes up his watch. It's 6:05. He straps the analog clock over his wrist, grabs his final remaining cash from his wallet, takes on his headphone, boots his jacket over his shoulder, and grabs his laptop bag as he opens his door.
He goes out into the walk path. The atmosphere was dark and humid. The cold winds fluttered over his face. Surrounded by a sense of ambience, he walks towards the café. He takes out his cigarette box, grabs one of the last two remaining cigarettes, lits it, starts smoking.

As he starts walking, his mind starts fluttering. He remembers this path. He used to take this with her a long time ago. The memories start rushing into his mind space. He exhales the smoke and tries to walk, but his mind keeps staggering and his legs keep faltering. Then he almost reaches close to the cafe door. He bumps into it, resulting in a flutter of ravens perching near the door. As he enters the door, he sees the phrase, Life happens written upon the door. He drops the cigarette, butts it out and enters the cafe.

He walks into the door. The waiter casually looks up to him and says, The usual? He nods his head and walks straight into the restroom. Nicotine protrudes his head. He looks in the mirror, splashes a wimp of cold water onto his face, shakes his head, trying to get to pause his faltering mind for a few seconds.

But to no avail, his neurons keep firing up. He grabs more water and throws it directly onto his face. He forcefully moves his hand up and down, his fingers get thrashed onto the slick tiles of the washroom, and his flesh slightly tears at the tips of his fingers.


Without him noticing, blood prickles down onto his palm and mixes with the water droplets on his palm. He grabs more water, his eyes still closed, splashes blood-diluted water over his face. His eyes open, and suddenly he looks into the mirror and he remembers that day in the rain when she fell into his arms. Her eyes looked stunning like lightning. As their hands clasped, he moved his face to his side, and then she pulled herself up. 

He comes to his senses, looks down on his hands, bloodied up, grabs a napkin, washes off his face, removes the blood droplets using the napkin and cleans his finger, drops the napkin back into the bin, walks out of the restroom door.

He starts walking towards his table. He removes the bag from his shoulder, takes out his laptop, connects it to the Wi-Fi, opens Docs, and there, it was as if his own mind was staring back into himself. The monitor displayed an empty white page with the cursor blinking. The page was titled, The End.

His mind starts faltering. Thoughts start seeping into his mind. What is the ending? How do I end it? Did it ever end? He starts questioning himself. When did it start? his mind responded. It should have his heart pacified him.

He closes his eyes for a moment, feels as if he's standing on a lonely rock, and suddenly, her memories come bashing over like wave hitting rocks. He shakes his head off to reduce the head spiral. He starts typing.

The clattering of the keys matched the rhythm of his broken heart. He closed his eyes for a moment. Her freckled face passed his thoughts. "We could never be that," her words echoed in his mind. "Maybe someday, in a different life," he thought.

Yes, we're more than just best friends, but that's about it I can come to think about it. Her last words on the day of their adieu protruded his heart. He opened his eyes and typed out the following

I felt ecstasy, when I knew your eyes;
I felt joy, when I saw your smile;
I felt romance, when your hands clasped mine;
I felt poetry, when I heard you speak;
I felt love, when your cheeks turned red;
I felt hope, when your eyes met mine;

But, Oh! 
My best friend, on the day of adieu, when you kissed my cheek in an embrace of warmth;
You told, you knew the depths of my broken heart;

Oh, But! 
How you never knew the feelings those shattered pieces of my broken heart held for you;
And you never will know how it crushed those shattered pieces of my heart to know that you never knew those unrequited feelings it had for you;

Oh, you! You never knew!


Something lifted off his chest. He breathed out relaxingly...It's been 52 weeks, his mind thought, since the last time we both talked. But people drift away, that's part of life, right? His heart spoke. He stammered for a moment, then took out his phone. His fingers clacked the keyboard. Her name came up. He gently pressed the button. It started ringing.

His heart raced a million seconds. Someone picked up. Hello? Is Riya there? He stammered. Oh, is her name Riya? A rather grumpy voice responded. She just got into an accident, the voice added. The ambulance and just drove off. His heart sank. Where did this happen? His mind echoed through his trembling voice over the phone. Lakeview Street, the voice responded. He cut the call and realized that street is just a block away.
He got up from his table walked out the door onto the road, checking his phone. Bam! He was hit by a passing-by ambulance. He fell over the edge of the road. His last cigarette fell out his pocket next  his hand's.The watch shattered out of his hand and  stopped at seven minutes to seven a.m. 

He started bleeding all over while lying in a pool of his blood, he twisted around and gazed towards the cafe and glazed over at the words, "Life happens." He turned his head towards the sky as the ravens over his head fluttered. The blood on his hand seeped over his last cigarette his hands were clutching. As the cold wind blew over his face, he inhaled and felt love at minus one degree Celsius.

A knife hidden at their back,
Poisoned food near to my mouth.
Rusty metal covered by a coating of gold;
Grudges plastered with buttered words.  
Mono-actors occupy the stage;
Innocent frogs living in the filthiest pond.
The tongue has two sides;
Ears are two, eyes are two,
But we have only one heart!  
What if you give a reply with my two hands?
Instead, we show thirty-two teeth in a grin.
Your own hands strangled your neck;
Your own actions make you step on thorns.  
Your own saliva turns toxic;
Your own nails scratch your skin.
How can we survive when your own parts tear you apart?  
Silence them with your skill;
Use sarcasm whenever you get the chance.
Direct sarcasm is far better than backbiting.  
Listen, my "trustworthy" traitors,
You don't even deserve hell.
They are purely demons;
They never do good, they only show off.  
Go on your way if your path is smooth;
Do not step into my path.
Better to jump into a well and perish!

